def MissingValues(wine):
    plt.figure(figsize=(18,6))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    MissingData=wine[wine.columns[wine.isnull().sum()>0]].isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False).to_frame()
    MissingData.columns = ['.isna()']
    MissingData['.isna()']
    p1=sns.barplot(x=MissingData.index, y='.isna()', data=MissingData)
    p1.set_xticklabels(p1.get_xticklabels(), rotation=90)
    p1.set_title('Missing Values From winedata')

#We can see from looking at the Product Name that most of these wines missing both the Varietal and Bottle Size seem to be 
#part of a gift set or promotional offer with one Bodacious Smooth Red looking to be a larger bag in the box type wine 
#We will set all wines with +,& offer, Special, Gift, set, Online, Exclusive 
NameMissingVariatel=wine[wine['Varietal'].isna()]['Product_Name'] # update list of wines missing Varietal
fixed_wine=[]
chosenwords=['+','&','offer','SPECIAL','OFFER', 'Special', 'Gift', 'set', 'Online', 'Exclusive','Kit']
for WINE in NameMissingVariatel:
        if any(word in WINE for word in chosenwords):
            for x in wine[(wine['Product_Name'])==WINE].index: #use for x in _ incase multiple wines with same name 
                fixed_wine.append(x)            
                wine.iloc[x, wine.columns.get_loc('Varietal')] = 'Gift Set/Special'
wine.iloc[fixed_wine].head()

wineLocation=wine['Made In'].fillna('Unknown')# change nan to string type so we can use our apply(split)
SplitMadein=wineLocation.apply(lambda x: x.split(','))

L1=[]
L2=[]
i=0
x=0
while i<len(SplitMadein):
    if len(SplitMadein[x])>1: # if we have a region and country
        L1.append(SplitMadein[x][0].replace(' ', '')) #need the .replace(' ', '') because we have... 'Germany' and ' Germany'.
        L2.append(SplitMadein[x][1].replace(' ', ''))
    else:     
        L1.append(np.nan) # if we only have one identifying location
        L2.append(SplitMadein[x][0].replace(' ', ''))
    x+=1    
    i+=1
Region=L1
Country=L2
wine['Region']=Region
wine['Country']=Country

#lets create a categorical bottle size column
def func(x):
    if 0 < x <=749:
        return 'Small :<750ml'
    elif 749 < x <= 751:
        return 'Normal :750ml'
    elif 751 < x <= 1500:
            return 'Large :>750ml'
    elif 1501 < x <= 5000:
            return 'X-Large :>1500ml'
    elif x==0: #recall from above that 0 values were 2x750', '3000mLbagnbox', ' '375mLgift', '4000mLbagnbox.... etc
        return 'Unique(Box/Gift Pack)'

wine['BottleCategorical'] = wine['BottleCategorical'].apply(func)

# Method for making Correlation plots
def winecorrplot(data=wine,dummies=x,highest=None,lowest=None,poi=None):
    wine_dummies = pd.get_dummies(data, columns=[dummies],drop_first=False)
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
    if highest==True: #select nlargest 
        highest=wine_dummies.corr().nlargest(5,columns=poi).index
        sns.heatmap(wine_dummies[highest].corr(),linecolor='white',linewidths=2,annot=True).set_title('Corr Matrix for '+poi+' and '+dummies+' (Highest)', fontsize=20)

    else: pass
    if lowest==True: #select nsmallest
        lowest=wine_dummies.corr().nsmallest(6,columns=poi).index.insert(0,poi)
        sns.heatmap(wine_dummies[lowest].corr(),linecolor='white',linewidths=2,annot=True).set_title('Corr Matrix for '+poi+' and '+dummies+' (Lowest)', fontsize=20)
    else:pass

On the other plot we can see wines from Canada have no added tariff or large transport costs and wines from the other countries like Chile and South Africa have a reputation of being cheaper and lower quality¶

positive_corr=[]
interests=['Varietal','Country','Alcohol/Vol','Style','Sugar Content','Sweetness Descriptor']# What we want dummy variables of
for d in interests:
    wine_dummies = pd.get_dummies(wine, columns=[d],drop_first=False)# need dummies since not all are catagorical number
    highest=wine_dummies.corr()
    for x in ['Case Price','Alcohol/Vol','Sugar Content']: #drop these to prevent them from appearing in other corr. 
        try: highest=highest.drop([x])
        except:pass
    highest=highest[highest>0].nlargest(11,columns='Price').index#positive correlation values only
    positive_corr.append(wine_dummies[highest].corr()['Price'])
#positive_corr

negative_corr=[]
#interest=['Varietal','Country','Alcohol/Vol','Style','Sugar Content','Sweetness Descriptor']
for d in interests:
    wine_dummies = pd.get_dummies(wine, columns=[d],drop_first=False,prefix=[' '])# need dummies since not all are a catagorical number
    negative=wine_dummies.corr()
    for x in ['Case Price','Alcohol/Vol','Sugar Content']: 
        try: 
            negative=negative.drop(x)
        except:pass
    negative=negative[negative<0].nsmallest(11,columns='Price').index.insert(0,'Price')# negative corr values only
    negative_corr.append(wine_dummies[negative].corr()['Price'])
# negative_corr
